definitions.definition: To pay, give in payment; repay, recompense; reward; requite.
To furnish; to afford; to render; to give forth.
To give way; to allow another to pass first.
definitions.example: Yield the right of way to pedestrians.

definitions.definition: To give as required; to surrender, relinquish or capitulate.
definitions.example: They refuse to yield to the enemy.

definitions.definition: To give way; to succumb to a force.
To produce as return, as from an investment.
definitions.example: Historically, that security yields a high return.
Adding 3 and 4 yields a result of 7.

definitions.definition: To produce a particular sound as the result of a sound law.
(of a material specimen) To pass the material's yield point and undergo plastic deformation.
To admit to be true; to concede; to allow.
A product; the quantity of something produced.
definitions.example: Zucchini plants always seem to produce a high yield of fruit.

definitions.definition: The current return as a percentage of the price of a stock or bond.
Profit earned from an investment; return on investment.
